                            "tilte" => "How to limit text to n lines with CSS?"
                            "slug" => "how-to-limit-text-to-n-lines-with-css2024-07-28-172133"
                            "short_details" => "Sometimes, we have to trim text to limit the number of lines. There are a few ways to do it with pure CSS. Let's learn how to achieve that The easiest way to limit text to n lines is to use line-clamp."
                            "details" => """
                              N can be any positive number, but it will be two or three lines most of the time. On my blog, I'm using line-clamp in all post-type components to ensure that it will have the same height as siblings.\r\n
                              \r\n
                              ### One-line truncation\r\n
                              To truncate only one line we can use:\r\n
                              \r\n
                              ```css\r\n
                              .truncate {\r\n
                                text-overflow: ellipsis;\r\n
                                overflow: hidden;\r\n
                                white-space: nowrap;\r\n
                              }\r\n
                              ```\r\n
                              \r\n
                              \r\n
                              White-space and overflow will do the job, while text-overflow will add three dots at the end of the line.\r\n
                              \r\n
                              than one line?\r\n
                              \r\n
                              ### Multiple lines truncation\r\n
                              The easiest way is to use this snippet:\r\n
                              \r\n
                              ```css\r\n
                              .truncate {\r\n
                                 overflow: hidden;\r\n
                                 text-overflow: ellipsis;\r\n
                                 display: -webkit-box;\r\n
                                 -webkit-line-clamp: 2; /* number of lines to show */\r\n
                                         line-clamp: 2;\r\n
                                 -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\r\n
                              }\r\n
                              ```\r\n
                              \r\n
                              We are using multiple CSS properties:\r\n
                              * overflow: hidden;\r\n
                              * text-overflow: ellipsis; - optional, it will add three dots at the end of the trimmed line\r\n
                              * display: -webkit-box;\r\n
                              * -webkit-line-clamp: 2; - here we can specify how many lines we want to show to the user\r\n
                              * line-clamp: 2;\r\n
                              * -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\r\n
                              \r\n
                              [Referance albertwalicki](https://albertwalicki.com/learn/solutions/how-to-limit-text-to-n-lines)
                              """

                          "tilte" => "How to limit text to n lines with CSS?"
                          "slug" => "how-to-limit-text-to-n-lines-with-css2024-07-28-172133"
                          "short_details" => "Sometimes, we have to trim text to limit the number of lines. There are a few ways to do it with pure CSS. Let's learn how to achieve that The easiest way to limit text to n lines is to use line-clamp."
                          "details" => """
                            N can be any positive number, but it will be two or three lines most of the time. On my blog, I'm using line-clamp in all post-type components to ensure that it will have the same height as siblings.\r\n
                            \r\n
                            ### One-line truncation\r\n
                            To truncate only one line we can use:\r\n
                            \r\n
                            ```css\r\n
                            .truncate {\r\n
                              text-overflow: ellipsis;\r\n
                              overflow: hidden;\r\n
                              white-space: nowrap;\r\n
                            }\r\n
                            ```\r\n
                            \r\n
                            \r\n
                            White-space and overflow will do the job, while text-overflow will add three dots at the end of the line.\r\n
                            \r\n
                            than one line?\r\n
                            \r\n
                            ### Multiple lines truncation\r\n
                            The easiest way is to use this snippet:\r\n
                            \r\n
                            ```css\r\n
                            .truncate {\r\n
                               overflow: hidden;\r\n
                               text-overflow: ellipsis;\r\n
                               display: -webkit-box;\r\n
                               -webkit-line-clamp: 2; /* number of lines to show */\r\n
                                       line-clamp: 2;\r\n
                               -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\r\n
                            }\r\n
                            ```\r\n
                            \r\n
                            We are using multiple CSS properties:\r\n
                            * overflow: hidden;\r\n
                            * text-overflow: ellipsis; - optional, it will add three dots at the end of the trimmed line\r\n
                            * display: -webkit-box;\r\n
                            * -webkit-line-clamp: 2; - here we can specify how many lines we want to show to the user\r\n
                            * line-clamp: 2;\r\n
                            * -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\r\n
                            \r\n
                            [Referance albertwalicki](https://albertwalicki.com/learn/solutions/how-to-limit-text-to-n-lines)
                            """

                          "short_details" => "In programming, the @ symbol can have different meanings depending on the context and the language being used. In many cases, it is used to denote special operations or to signify something in the code. Here’s a brief overview of its usage:"
                          "details" => """
                            1. **In PHP**: The `@` symbol is an error control operator. When prefixed to an expression, it suppresses any error messages that might be generated by that expression. For example:\r\n
                               ```php\r\n
                               @$parcel->total_delivery_amount\r\n
                               ```\r\n
                               In this case, if accessing `$parcel->total_delivery_amount` results in an error (e.g., if `$parcel` is null or the property does not exist), the error will be suppressed, and no warning will be shown.\r\n
                            \r\n
                            2. **In other contexts**:\r\n
                               - **In email addresses**: The `@` symbol separates the username from the domain name (e.g., `user@example.com`).\r\n
                               - **In Python (decorators)**: The `@` symbol is used to apply decorators to functions or methods (e.g., `@staticmethod`).\r\n
                               - **In other languages or frameworks**: The symbol can have different uses. For example, in some configuration files or frameworks, it might denote a special variable or syntax.\r\n
                            \r\n
                            If you are referring to a specific language or framework, providing more details might help in giving a more precise explanation.
                            """

                "tilte" => "How to limit text to n lines with CSS?"
                "slug" => "how-to-limit-text-to-n-lines-with-css2024-07-28-172133"
                "short_details" => "Sometimes, we have to trim text to limit the number of lines. There are a few ways to do it with pure CSS. Let's learn how to achieve that The easiest way to limit text to n lines is to use line-clamp."
                "details" => """
                  N can be any positive number, but it will be two or three lines most of the time. On my blog, I'm using line-clamp in all post-type components to ensure that it will have the same height as siblings.\r\n
                  \r\n
                  ### One-line truncation\r\n
                  To truncate only one line we can use:\r\n
                  \r\n
                  ```css\r\n
                  .truncate {\r\n
                    text-overflow: ellipsis;\r\n
                    overflow: hidden;\r\n
                    white-space: nowrap;\r\n
                  }\r\n
                  ```\r\n
                  \r\n
                  \r\n
                  White-space and overflow will do the job, while text-overflow will add three dots at the end of the line.\r\n
                  \r\n
                  than one line?\r\n
                  \r\n
                  ### Multiple lines truncation\r\n
                  The easiest way is to use this snippet:\r\n
                  \r\n
                  ```css\r\n
                  .truncate {\r\n
                     overflow: hidden;\r\n
                     text-overflow: ellipsis;\r\n
                     display: -webkit-box;\r\n
                     -webkit-line-clamp: 2; /* number of lines to show */\r\n
                             line-clamp: 2;\r\n
                     -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\r\n
                  }\r\n
                  ```\r\n
                  \r\n
                  We are using multiple CSS properties:\r\n
                  * overflow: hidden;\r\n
                  * text-overflow: ellipsis; - optional, it will add three dots at the end of the trimmed line\r\n
                  * display: -webkit-box;\r\n
                  * -webkit-line-clamp: 2; - here we can specify how many lines we want to show to the user\r\n
                  * line-clamp: 2;\r\n
                  * -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\r\n
                  \r\n
                  [Referance albertwalicki](https://albertwalicki.com/learn/solutions/how-to-limit-text-to-n-lines)
                  """

                "tilte" => "Different Meaning of @ and null error handling laravel"
                "slug" => "different-meaning-of-at-2024-07-28-070300"
                "short_details" => "In programming, the @ symbol can have different meanings depending on the context and the language being used. In many cases, it is used to denote special operations or to signify something in the code. Here’s a brief overview of its usage:"
                "details" => """
                  1. **In PHP**: The `@` symbol is an error control operator. When prefixed to an expression, it suppresses any error messages that might be generated by that expression. For example:\r\n
                     ```php\r\n
                     @$parcel->total_delivery_amount\r\n
                     ```\r\n
                     In this case, if accessing `$parcel->total_delivery_amount` results in an error (e.g., if `$parcel` is null or the property does not exist), the error will be suppressed, and no warning will be shown.\r\n
                  \r\n
                  2. **In other contexts**:\r\n
                     - **In email addresses**: The `@` symbol separates the username from the domain name (e.g., `user@example.com`).\r\n
                     - **In Python (decorators)**: The `@` symbol is used to apply decorators to functions or methods (e.g., `@staticmethod`).\r\n
                     - **In other languages or frameworks**: The symbol can have different uses. For example, in some configuration files or frameworks, it might denote a special variable or syntax.\r\n
                  \r\n
                  If you are referring to a specific language or framework, providing more details might help in giving a more precise explanation.
                  """
